British Galleries:
Chinese wallpapers and their European imitations were fashionable from the late 17th century onwards. They were used for bedrooms, dressing rooms and drawing rooms. Chinese wallpapers made for the western market were hand-painted. Their European imitations were usually printed or stencilled, although this English example is painted.

fields.historical_context_note:
[Wallpaper panel] In Britain, paper printed or painted with patterns has been used for decorating walls since the 16th century. In the 18th century hand-painted Chinese wallpapers became very popular in Europe, and especially in Britain. These wallpapers were very expensive, however, and only the aristocracy and other wealthy people could afford them. Even so, demand exceeded supply. This encouraged European manufacturers to produce designs in the Chinese style.

Materials & Making
Chinese wallpapers were produced in sets of 25 or 40 lengths, sufficient to decorate a whole room. Each length was a different design, but when hung in sequence around the room they made up a panoramic landscape decoration. This panel (one of seven) was made in Britain, but it imitates the style and the methods of the Chinese papers very closely. It has been hand-painted, and the artist has tried to copy the Chinese way of drawing the trees, flowers and birds. The result is not entirely convincing, partly because the colours are not as bright as those used for the genuine Chinese wallpapers. Also, the flowers are fanciful and rather crudely drawn, whereas those in the Chinese papers were usually identifiable species. These wallpaper panels vary in size and were probably made specifically for the room in Berkeley House, Wotton-under-Edge, in which they were found.

Ownership & Use
In Britain in the 18th century the Chinese papers (and British imitations of them) were often hung in those apartments which were used mostly by women, such as dressing rooms (where women often entertained female guests and family members) and drawing rooms (where women gathered after dinner). At that time the exotic imagery and informal asymmetric designs of these wallpapers were associated with feminine qualities.
